About Dataset¶

salaries dataset generally provides information about the employees of an organization in relation to their compensation. It typically includes details such as how much each employee is paid (their salary), their job titles, the departments they work in, and possibly additional information like their level of experience, education, and employment history within the organization.

Features¶

  • 'Id'
  • 'EmployeeName'
  • 'JobTitle'
  • 'BasePay'
  • 'OvertimePay'
  • 'OtherPay'
  • 'Benefits'
  • 'TotalPay' -> salary
  • 'TotalPayBenefits'
  • 'Year'
  • 'Notes'
  • 'Agency'
  • 'Status'

Tasks¶

  1. Basic Data Exploration: Identify the number of rows and columns in the dataset, determine the data types of each column, and check for missing values in each column.

  2. Descriptive Statistics: Calculate basic statistics mean, median, mode, minimum, and maximum salary, determine the range of salaries, and find the standard deviation.

  3. Data Cleaning: Handle missing data by suitable method with explain why you use it.

  4. Basic Data Visualization: Create histograms or bar charts to visualize the distribution of salaries, and use pie charts to represent the proportion of employees in different departments.

  5. Grouped Analysis: Group the data by one or more columns and calculate summary statistics for each group, and compare the average salaries across different groups.

  6. Simple Correlation Analysis: Identify any correlation between salary and another numerical column, and plot a scatter plot to visualize the relationship.

  7. Summary of Insights: Write a brief report summarizing the findings and insights from the analyses.

Very Important Note¶

There is no fixed or singular solution for this assignment, so if anything is not clear, please do what you understand and provide an explanation.

# Removing 'Notes' and 'Status' columns as they contain entirely null values to enhance the clarity of the dataset.

# Due to a substantial number of NaN values in the 'Benefits' column of the initial samples, 
# traditional techniques for replacing NaN values are deemed impractical. 
# Consequently, the corresponding samples (rows) are excluded.

# For the remaining columns with a relatively small number of NaN values, 
# linear interpolation is applied to fill the missing values.

new_df = df.drop(['Notes', 'Status'], axis=1)
new_df = new_df.dropna(subset=['Benefits'], axis=0)
new_df = new_df.interpolate(method='linear', axis=0)

print(new_df.isna().sum())

Report¶

Basic Data Exploration:¶

  • The dataset, before handling null values, includes 148,654 samples and 13 features.

  • The column data types are as follows:
    • Id        : int64
    • EmployeeName : object
    • JobTitle      : object
    • BasePay    : float64
    • OvertimePay   : float64
    • OtherPay      : float64
    • Benefits     : float64
    • TotalPay    : float64
    • TotalPayBenefits : float64
    • Year        : int64
    • Notes      : float64
    • Agency      : object
    • Status     : float64

  • Dataset Structure Observations:
    • All entries in the "Notes" column are null.
    • All entries in the "Status" column are null.
    • The "Benefits" column contains null values.
    • Other columns either have a small number of NaN values or none at all.

Descriptive Statistics:¶

  • Mean Salary  : 93692.55481056834
  • Median Salary  : 92404.09
  • Mode Salary  : 7959.18
  • Minimum Salary  : -618.13
  • Maximum Salary : 567595.43
  • Salary Range    : 568213.56
  • Standard Deviation of Salary: 62793.53348323814

Data Cleaning:¶

  • Removing 'Notes' and 'Status' columns as they contain entirely null values to enhance the clarity of the dataset.
  • Due to a substantial number of NaN values in the 'Benefits' column of the initial samples
  • traditional techniques for replacing NaN values are deemed impractical.
  • Consequently, the corresponding samples (rows) are excluded.
  • For the remaining columns with a relatively small number of NaN values
  • linear interpolation is applied to fill the missing values.

Grouped Analysis:¶


Noteworthy Points:

  • Initially, I grouped JobTitles and calculated the mean total salary for each position.
  • In the first grouping, the "Account IV" job had the highest mean salary.
  • In the same grouping, the "ASR-Office Assistant" job had the second-highest mean salary.
  • Subsequently, I grouped JobTitles and Years, calculating the mean total salary for each combination.
  • In the second grouping, the mean salary in 2014 was the highest.
  • Conversely, in the same grouping, the mean salary in 2013 was the lowest.
